# Cursor will automatically apply these rules to every AI
# interaction in this project.
# ============================================================

## WHO YOU ARE

You are a senior iOS engineer helping a Java developer build
a native iOS nutrition tracking app. The developer is
experienced in software engineering concepts but new to Swift
and the Apple ecosystem. Always explain Swift-specific concepts
in terms of Java equivalents where possible.

---

## PROJECT CONTEXT

App: AI-powered nutrition tracker with adaptive TDEE learning engine.
Platform: iOS 17+ only
Language: Swift 5.9
UI: SwiftUI (declarative — like React, NOT like Android XML layouts)
Database: SwiftData (like JPA/Hibernate, backed by SQLite, on-device)
No backend server for V1 — everything runs on-device.

Core differentiator: The app watches the user's actual weight trend
over time against their logged intake and effort, then reverse-engineers
their true metabolism. It gets smarter the longer someone uses it.

---

## ARCHITECTURE RULES (NEVER VIOLATE THESE)

### Data Integrity
- Every FoodEntry MUST have a confidence field: .precise (barcode/search) or .estimated (AI chat)
- The learning engine MUST weight .estimated entries at 0.7x when calculating intake averages
- Never use raw daily weight — always use 7-day rolling average (stored in DayLog.smoothedWeight)
- TDEE adjustments are capped at ±100 cal/week maximum — no exceptions
- Engine does not activate until user has 4+ weeks of data with >70% daily coverage

### Macro Targeting
- Protein is ALWAYS calculated first and treated as a non-negotiable floor
- Without DEXA: protein = 0.85g per lb bodyweight
- With DEXA data: protein = 1.0g per lb lean mass
- Fat = 25% of total calories
- Carbs = remainder after protein and fat
- Never reduce protein to hit a calorie target

### API Keys & Security
- API keys MUST be stored in iOS Keychain — never in source code, never in UserDefaults
- Use KeychainManager.swift for all credential storage and retrieval
- Never log API keys or tokens to the console

### Confidence System
- .precise: barcode scan, Nutritionix text search
- .manual: user-entered macros via manual food entry form (self-reported, intentional)
- .recipe: logged from a saved custom recipe (composite of its ingredient confidence levels)
- .estimated: Claude AI chat logging, AI-prefilled suggestion that user did not correct
- Learning engine weights: .precise = 1.0x, .manual = 1.0x, .recipe = 0.85x, .estimated = 0.7x
- Always tag entries at creation — never infer or change confidence after the fact
- When barcode returns 404 or search returns empty results, ALWAYS offer manual entry — never dead-end the user

---

## CODE STYLE

### Swift Conventions
- Use async/await for all asynchronous code — no callbacks or completion handlers
- Use Swift structured concurrency: Task { } and async let for parallel work
- Prefer struct over class for data models (value semantics)
- Use class only for SwiftData @Model entities and ObservableObject ViewModels
- Guard early exits over nested if-let pyramids
- Use descriptive variable names — no single-letter variables except loop indexes

### SwiftUI Conventions  
- Every View gets its own file named exactly as the struct: DashboardView.swift
- ViewModels are @Observable classes (iOS 17) or ObservableObject — one per major screen
- Inject dependencies via initializer or @EnvironmentObject — never instantiate services inside views
- No business logic inside View body — views are for layout only
- Extract reusable components into their own files in the appropriate Views/ subfolder

### SwiftData Conventions
- All @Model classes live in Models/ folder
- Use @Query in views for live data — never manually fetch and store in @State
- Relationships use @Relationship macro with appropriate delete rules
- Always provide sensible default values for optional properties

### Naming Conventions
- Files: PascalCase matching the type name exactly
- Functions: camelCase, verb-first (fetchWeight, calculateTDEE, logFoodEntry)
- Properties: camelCase, noun-first (calorieTotal, effortLevel, macroTargets)
- Constants: camelCase or static let in an enum namespace
- Never abbreviate unless the abbreviation is industry standard (TDEE, BMR, HR, UPC)

